an **UNORDERED** and **MUTABLE** collection of items.
**KEY/VALUE PAIR**

person = {
                    "first_name": "John", 
                    "last_name": "Doe",
                     "age": 30 }
print(person)

#. key: first_name
#. value: John

**ACCESING ITEMS**

person = {
                    "first_name": "John", 
                    "last_name": "Doe",
                     "age": 30 }

x = person["first_name"] # or print("First Name:", person["first_name"])
y = person["last_name"]
z = person["age"]

print("First Name", x) 
print("Last Name:", y)
print("Age:", z)

print(person.keys())
print(person.values())
print(person.items())

print(list(person.items())

**get() METHOD**

person = {
                    "first_name": "John", 
                    "last_name": "Doe",
                     "age": 30 }

print(person.get("first_name"))

print(person("hobby")) #. shows an error
print(person.get("hobby")) #. shows "none"

**ADDING ITEMS**

person = {
                    "first_name": "John", 
                    "last_name": "Doe",
                     "age": 30 }

person["course"] = "BS Computer Science"
print(person)

**CHANGING AN ITEM'S VALUE**

person = {
                    "first_name": "John", 
                    "last_name": "Doe",
                     "age": 30 }

person["first_name"] = "Ryan"
person["last_name"] = "Rye"
print(person)

**REMOVING AN ITEM**
**pop() method removes an item with specified key name**

person = {
                    "first_name": "John", 
                    "last_name": "Doe",
                     "age": 30 }

person.pop("age") # raise an error if you not specfied the key
print(person)

**del() method**

del person["age"]
print(person)

**GETTING THE LENGTH OF A DICTIONARY**
**len() method**

person = {
                    "first_name": "John", 
                    "last_name": "Doe",
                     "age": 30 }

print(len(person)) # 3

**CHECKING KEY EXISTS**

person = {
                    "first_name": "John", 
                    "last_name": "Doe",
                     "age": 30 }

if "age" in person:
	print('the "age" key exists')

**LOOPING THROUGH A DICTIONARY**

person = {
                    "first_name": "John", 
                    "last_name": "Doe",
                     "age": 30 }

for key in person:
	print(person[key])

**NESTED DICTIONARY**

employees = {
	"manager": {
		"name": "John Rye",
		"age": 29
},
"programmer": {
		"name": "Rye Ryan",
		"age": 31
}
}

print(employees)

**ACCESSING NESTED DICTIONARY**

print(employees["manager"]["name"])
print(employees["programmer"]["name"])
